scenarioDescription:
The TOI-1266 Exoplanetary System


Overview

TOI-1266 is a star with 0.45 times the mass of the Sun, and 0.42 times its radius. It is located NaN light years away from the solar system.

TOI-1266 is known to have undefined exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the TOI-1266 system


TOI-1266 b

TOI-1266 b was discovered by the undefined observatory using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.07 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of TOI-1266 b is 13.50864 times the mass of Earth. The radius of TOI-1266 b is 2.37 that of Earth. At more than 10 Earth masses, TOI-1266 b is an ice giant, a planet that is made up mostly of volatiles like water, amonia and methane, and enveloped by a dense hydrogen and helium atmosphere, much like Uranus and Neptune in our solar system.


TOI-1266 c

TOI-1266 c was discovered by the undefined observatory using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.11 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of TOI-1266 c is 2.20056 times the mass of Earth. The radius of TOI-1266 c is 1.56 that of Earth. At 2.20056 Earth masses, TOI-1266 c is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.
